title: Chase Utley not in Dodgers lineup for Game 3 vs. Mets
text:
Ruben Tejada collides with Chase Utley at second base in the 7th inning. (Photo: Jayne Kamin-Oncea, USA TODAY Sports)
162 CONNECT 15 TWEET LINKEDIN 1 COMMENT EMAIL MORE Chase Utley is not in the Dodgers lineup for Game 3 of the National League Division Series against the Mets.
The Dodgers second baseman, who is appealing a two-game suspension handed down by Major League Baseball for his hard slide on Mets shortstop Ruben Tejada in Game 2, is eligible to play until his appeal is heard.
The appeal was not heard Monday because MLB and the players' association did not have sufficient time to prepare.
USA TODAY
With little time for hearing, Chase Utley likely to be eligible for Games 3, 4
Here is the Dodgers' lineup, which features Howie Kendrick starting at second once again, but has Jimmy Rollins replacing rookie Corey Seager at shortstop:
#Dodgers lineup: Kendrick 2B, Rollins SS, Gonzalez 1B, Turner 3B, Ethier RF
L, Crawford LF, Grandal C, Hernandez CF, Anderson P.
— Dylan Hernandez (@dylanohernandez) October 12, 2015 In a prepared statement on Sunday, MLB chief baseball officer Joe Torre said "Mr. Utley's action warrants discipline. While I sincerely believe that Mr. Utley had no intention of injuring Ruben Tejada, and was attempting to help his club in a critical situation, I believe his slide was in violation of Official Baseball Rule 5.09 (a)(13), which is designed to protect from precisely this type of rolling block that occurs away from the base."
Utley collided with Tejada on a hard and late slide into second base in an attempt to break up a double play during the seventh inning of Game 2. Tejada suffered a broken right fibula on the play.
Utley defended his slide and has said he had no attempt to intentionally hurt Tejada.
"I was trying to put a body on him to try to break up a double play," said Utley after Game 2. “You're taught from a young age to try to break up double plays. I think that's winning baseball. Anybody in that situation ... my focus is seeing the ball. I didn't realize his back was turned. Everything obviously happens fast."
The specter of Utley in the lineup could have prompted Mets starter Matt Harvey to retaliate against Utley with a brushback pitch. Utley has a good track record against Harvey, with a .984 OPS in 21 career plate appearances.
The Dodgers, however, will stick with Kendrick, whose hamstring injury prompted the Dodgers to acquire Utley from the Philadelphia Phillies in August.
